00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:05.480
up. It was sold out in less than a week. And our only constraint now is space. We are physically

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:10.620
out of room to hold more people who want to come. So for the 10th anniversary, we put

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:16.680
up this graph here showing our membership growth. Zoomed in, it looks like this. I created

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:24.760
this graph originally for our 10th anniversary, and we went from 21 people to 10,697. Since

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:33.760
then, we're now at 11,205 as of this morning. So about 1,000 people a year joined the meetup.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:38.080
This is a picture from the first meetup. In fact, there might be someone in this room

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:44.919
in there. And it was a small crowd, and we had a ton of space to work with here, because

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:50.519
not that many people showed up. About 10 years later, it turned into this. We have

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:57.680
a lot more people coming now, and we also take really epic selfies. So beyond the New

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:00.760
York R meetup, which I'm obviously partial to, which is, by the way, no longer called

